<paragraph blockId="6.[264,1325,1399,1905]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis box="[312,450,1679,1704]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Description</emphasis>
. —Carapace with umbo on anterior margin, similar in males and females (
<figureCitation box="[273,346,1719,1745]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[264,367,1723,1747]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leptestheria brevispina, new species, MBUCV XI­ 3743: A. Lateral view of male carapace; B. Lateral view of female carapace; C. Lateral view of male head region; D. Lateral view of female head region; E. Male antenna; F. Female antenna; G. Clasper of male first thoracopod; H. Female first thoracopod; I. Female seventh thoracopod; J. Male telson region; K. Female telson region; Scale bars = 1 mm." pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[332,346,1719,1745]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
A,B). Males and females similar in size. Area between growth lines granulated, growth lines with row of delicate short setae (
<figureCitation box="[822,894,1759,1785]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[264,367,1723,1747]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leptestheria brevispina, new species, MBUCV XI­ 3743: A. Lateral view of male carapace; B. Lateral view of female carapace; C. Lateral view of male head region; D. Lateral view of female head region; E. Male antenna; F. Female antenna; G. Clasper of male first thoracopod; H. Female first thoracopod; I. Female seventh thoracopod; J. Male telson region; K. Female telson region; Scale bars = 1 mm." pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[879,894,1759,1785]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
B). Head with short, blunt occipital spine in both sexes (
<figureCitation box="[516,589,1799,1825]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[264,367,1723,1747]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leptestheria brevispina, new species, MBUCV XI­ 3743: A. Lateral view of male carapace; B. Lateral view of female carapace; C. Lateral view of male head region; D. Lateral view of female head region; E. Male antenna; F. Female antenna; G. Clasper of male first thoracopod; H. Female first thoracopod; I. Female seventh thoracopod; J. Male telson region; K. Female telson region; Scale bars = 1 mm." pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[575,589,1799,1825]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
C, D). Anterior margin straight to convex. Ocellus at rostral base, variable in shape. Male and female rostrum angularly shaped with short fornices meeting at rostral apex (
<figureCitation box="[553,623,1879,1905]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[264,367,1723,1747]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leptestheria brevispina, new species, MBUCV XI­ 3743: A. Lateral view of male carapace; B. Lateral view of female carapace; C. Lateral view of male head region; D. Lateral view of female head region; E. Male antenna; F. Female antenna; G. Clasper of male first thoracopod; H. Female first thoracopod; I. Female seventh thoracopod; J. Male telson region; K. Female telson region; Scale bars = 1 mm." pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[609,623,1879,1905]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
C, D). Both sexes with sharp spine situated at rostral apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[264,1323,284,1670]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
First antenna indistinctly segmented, with 
<number box="[766,835,284,310]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="14.5" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="13.0">13­16</number>
lobes bearing sensory setae in males and 
<number box="[264,311,324,350]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="9.5" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="8.0">8­11</number>
lobes in females (
<figureCitation box="[532,604,324,350]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[264,367,1723,1747]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leptestheria brevispina, new species, MBUCV XI­ 3743: A. Lateral view of male carapace; B. Lateral view of female carapace; C. Lateral view of male head region; D. Lateral view of female head region; E. Male antenna; F. Female antenna; G. Clasper of male first thoracopod; H. Female first thoracopod; I. Female seventh thoracopod; J. Male telson region; K. Female telson region; Scale bars = 1 mm." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Fig. 
<number box="[590,604,324,350]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
C, D). Male second antenna with peduncle indistinctly segmented and with 
<number box="[475,504,364,390]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="10.0">10</number>
segments in both flagella, each segment with 
<number box="[1066,1106,364,390]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="3.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="2.0">2­5</number>
dorsal spines and ventral long setae (
<figureCitation box="[492,562,404,430]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[264,367,1723,1747]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leptestheria brevispina, new species, MBUCV XI­ 3743: A. Lateral view of male carapace; B. Lateral view of female carapace; C. Lateral view of male head region; D. Lateral view of female head region; E. Male antenna; F. Female antenna; G. Clasper of male first thoracopod; H. Female first thoracopod; I. Female seventh thoracopod; J. Male telson region; K. Female telson region; Scale bars = 1 mm." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Fig. 
<number box="[548,562,404,430]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
E). Female second antenna similar to male but with 
<number box="[1189,1204,404,430]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="9.0">9</number>
segments on both flagella, and 
<number box="[520,559,444,470]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="2.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="1.0">1­4</number>
dorsal spines on each segment (
<figureCitation box="[950,1022,444,470]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[264,367,1723,1747]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leptestheria brevispina, new species, MBUCV XI­ 3743: A. Lateral view of male carapace; B. Lateral view of female carapace; C. Lateral view of male head region; D. Lateral view of female head region; E. Male antenna; F. Female antenna; G. Clasper of male first thoracopod; H. Female first thoracopod; I. Female seventh thoracopod; J. Male telson region; K. Female telson region; Scale bars = 1 mm." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Fig. 
<number box="[1007,1022,444,470]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
F). Male first thoracopod stout, with slight indentation at base of immovable finger (
<figureCitation box="[953,1022,484,510]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[264,367,1723,1747]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leptestheria brevispina, new species, MBUCV XI­ 3743: A. Lateral view of male carapace; B. Lateral view of female carapace; C. Lateral view of male head region; D. Lateral view of female head region; E. Male antenna; F. Female antenna; G. Clasper of male first thoracopod; H. Female first thoracopod; I. Female seventh thoracopod; J. Male telson region; K. Female telson region; Scale bars = 1 mm." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Fig. 
<number box="[1008,1022,484,510]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
G). Movable finger stout, strongly curved with truncated apex. Distal end with blunt spines on ventral margin. Immovable finger stout, with stout, large, thick acute spines on clasping border. Endite 
<number box="[1308,1323,564,590]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="4.0">4</number>
stout, with simple terminal setae. Endite 
<number box="[741,756,604,630]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="5.0">5</number>
(palp) stout, with two segments, with setae only on distal segment. Total length of palp near half length of movable finger. Endite 
<number box="[1308,1323,644,670]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="1.0">1</number>
strongly curved, with acute tip bearing two serrate terminal spines. Endite 
<number box="[1152,1167,684,710]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="2.0">2</number>
and 
<number box="[1227,1242,684,710]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="3.0">3</number>
lobed, with pedunculate setae. Female first thoracopod with setose lobe on anterior side (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[264,367,1723,1747]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leptestheria brevispina, new species, MBUCV XI­ 3743: A. Lateral view of male carapace; B. Lateral view of female carapace; C. Lateral view of male head region; D. Lateral view of female head region; E. Male antenna; F. Female antenna; G. Clasper of male first thoracopod; H. Female first thoracopod; I. Female seventh thoracopod; J. Male telson region; K. Female telson region; Scale bars = 1 mm." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Fig. 
<number box="[264,278,764,790]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
H). Female seventh, eighth and ninth throracopod with epipods swollen and cylindrical in shape (
<figureCitation box="[349,420,804,830]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[264,367,1723,1747]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leptestheria brevispina, new species, MBUCV XI­ 3743: A. Lateral view of male carapace; B. Lateral view of female carapace; C. Lateral view of male head region; D. Lateral view of female head region; E. Male antenna; F. Female antenna; G. Clasper of male first thoracopod; H. Female first thoracopod; I. Female seventh thoracopod; J. Male telson region; K. Female telson region; Scale bars = 1 mm." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Fig. 
<number box="[405,420,804,830]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="3.0">
<date box="[405,420,804,830]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">3</date>
</number>
</figureCitation>
I). Male telson with two rows of 
<number box="[818,886,804,830]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="17.0" valueMax="18.0" valueMin="16.0">16­18</number>
sharp spines, some of them smaller, with others bigger ones intercalated (
<figureCitation box="[700,770,844,870]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[264,367,1723,1747]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leptestheria brevispina, new species, MBUCV XI­ 3743: A. Lateral view of male carapace; B. Lateral view of female carapace; C. Lateral view of male head region; D. Lateral view of female head region; E. Male antenna; F. Female antenna; G. Clasper of male first thoracopod; H. Female first thoracopod; I. Female seventh thoracopod; J. Male telson region; K. Female telson region; Scale bars = 1 mm." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Fig. 
<number box="[755,770,844,870]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
J). Telsonal filaments delicate, plumose on distal half, arising at level of first telsonal spine. Female telson more slender than in male, with two rows of 
<number box="[471,500,924,950]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="18.0">18</number>
minute spines (
<figureCitation box="[685,754,924,950]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[264,367,1723,1747]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leptestheria brevispina, new species, MBUCV XI­ 3743: A. Lateral view of male carapace; B. Lateral view of female carapace; C. Lateral view of male head region; D. Lateral view of female head region; E. Male antenna; F. Female antenna; G. Clasper of male first thoracopod; H. Female first thoracopod; I. Female seventh thoracopod; J. Male telson region; K. Female telson region; Scale bars = 1 mm." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Fig. 
<number box="[740,754,924,950]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
K).
</paragraph>
